<section xml:id="section-week9-activity">
  <title>Week 9 Activity</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-orthogonal-matrices">
    <title>Orthogonal Matrices}</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine which of these matrices are orthogonal. For the
          matrices which are not orthogonal, clearly state how they
          fail the orthogonality criteria. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              a) \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
                -1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
                0 \amp 1 \amp 2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              b) \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{38}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{19}} \amp
                  \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{38}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{19}} \amp 
                  \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
                \frac{-6}{\sqrt{38}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{19}} \amp 
                  0 \\
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              c) \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                \frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{29}} \amp 
                  \frac{-2}{\sqrt{174}} \\
                \frac{-1}{\sqrt{6}} \amp \frac{4}{\sqrt{29}} \amp 
                  \frac{7}{\sqrt{174}} \\
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \amp \frac{-2}{\sqrt{29}} \amp 
                  \frac{11}{\sqrt{174}} 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              d) \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                \frac{3}{\sqrt{17}} \amp \frac{-2}{\sqrt{13}} \amp 
                  \frac{-6}{\sqrt{173}} \\
                \frac{-2}{\sqrt{17}} \amp 0 \amp 
                  \frac{-11}{\sqrt{173}} \\
                \frac{-2}{\sqrt{17}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{13}} \amp 
                  \frac{4}{\sqrt{173}} 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In a), the columns are pairwise orthogonal; we can check
          that all the dot products are zero.
          <md>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ -1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ -1 \\  0 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ -1 \\ 2 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ -1 \\ 2
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          However, the columns are not unit vectors. The length of the
          first column is <m>\sqrt{2}</m>, the second is
          <m>\sqrt{3}{</m> and the third if <m>\sqrt{6}</m>. An
          orthogonal matrix has to have columns of length one, so this
          is not an orthogonal matrix. 
        </p>
        <p>
          In b), the columns are pairwise orthogonal; we can check
          that all the dot products are zero. (Not that for these
          checks, we can scale the vectors as we wish, since whether
          or not the dot product is zero doesn't depend on the
          scaling. I've scale the columns to remove the square roots
          to make these calculations easier.) 
          <md>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1 \\ -6 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                3 \\ 3 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1 \\ -6 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ -1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                3 \\ 3 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ -1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          In addition, the column vectors all have length one. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left| \begin{matrix} 
                \frac{1}{sqrt{38}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{38}} \\
                \frac{-6}{\sqrt{38}}
              \end{matrix} \right| \amp = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{38}} \left| \begin{matrix} 
                1 \\ 1 \\ -6 
              \end{matrix} \right| = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{38}} \sqrt{1^2 + 1^2 + (-6)^2} =
              \frac{\sqrt{38}}{\sqrt{38}} = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left| \begin{matrix} 
                \frac{3}{\sqrt{19}} \\ \frac{3}{\sqrt{19}} \\
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{19}}
              \end{matrix} \right| \amp = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{19}} \left| \begin{matrix} 
                3 \\ 3 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right| = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{19}} \sqrt{3^2 + 3^2 + 1^2} =
              \frac{\sqrt{19}}{\sqrt{19}} = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left| \begin{matrix} 
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\ \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right| \amp = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left| \begin{matrix} 
                1 \\ -1 \\ 0
              \end{matrix} \right| = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \sqrt{1^2 + (-1)^2 + 0^2} =
              \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}} = 1 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          In c), the columns are pairwise orthogonal; we can check
          that all the dot products are zero. (Not that for these
          checks, we can scale the vectors as we wish, since whether
          or not the dot product is zero doesn't depend on the
          scaling. I've scale the columns to remove the square roots
          to make these calculations easier.) 
          <md>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                2 \\ -1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                3 \\ 4 \\ -2 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                2 \\ -1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -2 \\ 7 \\ 11 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                3 \\ 4 \\ -2 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -2 \\ 7 \\ 11
              \end{matrix} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          In addition, the column vectors all have length one. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left| \begin{matrix} 
                \sqrt{2}{\sqrt{6}} \\ \frac{-1}{\sqrt{6}} \\ 
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
              \end{matrix} \right| \amp = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \left| \begin{matrix} 
                2 \\ -1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right| = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \sqrt{2^2 + (-1)^2 + 1^2} =
              \frac{\sqrt{6}}{\sqrt{6}} = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left| \begin{matrix} 
                \frac{3}{\sqrt{29}} \\ \frac{4}{\sqrt{29}} \\
                \frac{-2}{\sqrt{29}}
              \end{matrix} \right| \amp = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{29}} \left| \begin{matrix} 
                3 \\ 4 \\ -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{29}} \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2 + (-2)^2} =
              \frac{\sqrt{29}}{\sqrt{29}} = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left| \begin{matrix} 
                \frac{-2}{\sqrt{174}} \\ \frac{7}{sqrt{174}} \\
                \frac{11}{\sqrt{174}} 
              \end{matrix} \right| \amp = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{174}} \left| \begin{matrix} 
                -2 \\ 7 \\ 11 
              \end{matrix} \right| = 
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{174}} \sqrt{(-2)^2 + 7^2 + (11)^2} =
              \frac{\sqrt{174}}{\sqrt{174}} = 1 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          In d), the columns are not pairwise orthogonal; we can check
          to see that this fails with the first and third columns.
          <md>
            <mrow>  
              \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                3 \\ -2 \\ -2 
              \end{matrix} \right) \cdot
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -6 \\ -11 \\ 4 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = (3)(-6) + (-2)(-11) + (-2)(-4) = -18 + 22 + 8 =
              12 \neq 0
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Since the columns are not orthogonal, this cannot be an
          orthogonal matrix. (We could check that the columns are unit
          vectors, which indeed they are, but we don't need to since
          we've already show that this cannot match the criteria for
          othogonality). 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For this incomplete matrix, add a final column which
          produces an orthogonal matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{5}{\sqrt{41}} \amp \cdot \\
              \frac{4}{\sqrt{41}} \amp \cdot \\
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We simply need to add a vector of length one which is
          perpendicular to the given column. If we switch the terms in
          the vector and make one of them negative, we can accomplish
          this. (This isn't an algorithmic solution; this is
          essentially by inspection. I'm looking at the matrix and
          making a guess based on my familiarity with vectors in
          <m>\RR^2</m>.)
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{5}{\sqrt{41}} \amp \frac{-4}{\sqrt{41}} \\
              \frac{4}{\sqrt{41}} \amp \frac{5}{\sqrt{41}}  \\
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          Note there are two possible answers; if we choose to make
          the other component negative, the following is another
          option. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{5}{\sqrt{41}} \amp \frac{4}{\sqrt{41}} \\
              \frac{4}{\sqrt{41}} \amp \frac{-5}{\sqrt{41}}  \\
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          These are, however, the only two possible solutions. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For this incomplete matrix, add a final column which
          produces an orthogonal matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{-3}{\sqrt{22}} \amp 
                \cdot \\
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{22}} \amp 
                \cdot \\
              0 \amp \frac{-2}{\sqrt{22}} \amp \cdot 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Unlike the previous matrix, this is much harder to do by
          inspection. Fortunately, we have an algorithmic approach. We
          want a new vector in <m>\RR^3</m> which is orthogonal to two
          given vector (the two columns). In <m>\RR^3</m>, the cross
          product gives exactly this desired vector. Let's take the
          cross product of the two columns. For ease of calculation,
          I'll scale the vectors to remove the denominators to find
          this third vector, since all I care about at this point is
          orthogonality. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              1 \\ 1 \\ 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) \times
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -3 \\ 3 \\ -2 
            \end{matrix} \right) = 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -2 \\ 2 \\ 6 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          This produces a vector othogonal to both columns. Now we
          want to scale it so that it is unit vector. The length of
          this vector is <m>\sqrt{(-2)^2 + 2^2 + 6^2} =
          \sqrt{44}</m>, so we divide by this to make a unit vector.
          That produces this orthogonal matrix. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{-3}{\sqrt{22}} \amp 
                \frac{-2}{\sqrt{44}}  \\
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{22}} \amp 
                \frac{2}{\sqrt{44}}  \\
              0 \amp \frac{-2}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{6}{\sqrt{44}}
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          Note, again, that there are two possible answers. If we did
          the cross-product in the other order, we would get the same
          vector multiplied by <m>(-1)</m>. That produces this other
          answer. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{-3}{\sqrt{22}} \amp 
                \frac{2}{\sqrt{44}}  \\
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{22}} \amp 
                \frac{-2}{\sqrt{44}}  \\
              0 \amp \frac{-2}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{-6}{\sqrt{44}}
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          These are the only two solution.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For this incomplete matrix, add a final column which
          produces an orthogonal matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp
                \cdot \\
              0 \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp \cdot \\
              \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp
                \cdot \\
              0 \amp \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp \cdot \\
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Now we again lack an algorithmic approach, since we don't
          have a cross product in <m>\RR^4</m>. So we have to try to
          work by inspection again, which is tricky. Looking at the
          first and third columns, these are only non-zero in the
          first and third coordinates. The second column is non-zero
          only in the second and fourth coordinate. We might try to
          match the second column and take zeros in the first and
          third components; that guarantees orthogonality with the
          first and third vector. Then we need to choose components to
          be orthogonal to the second column; that can be done by
          copying the second colum and setting one of the components
          to be negative. That gives the following answer. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp
                0  \\
              0 \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp 
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
              \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp
                0 \\
              0 \amp \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp 0 \amp
                \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-dihedral-groups">
    <title>Dihedral Groups</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Make a multiplication table for the dihedral group
          <m>D_5</m>. (Label the rotations <m>R_i</m>; the index
          <m>i</m> indicates how many fifth of a full turn for the
          rotation. Label the reflections <m>F_i</m>; the index
          indicates reflection over a line through the <m>i</m>
          vertex, counting counterclockwise.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There are many multiplications to calculate. I recommend
          calculating matrices by vertex operations. If we number the
          vertices of the pentagon counterclockwise from 1 to 5, then
          <m>R_2</m> (rotation by <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> of a turn) can be
          represented by this movement of vertices.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Reflection <m>F_3</m> (reflection over the line through
          vertex 3 and the middle of the opposite edge)) can be
          represented by this action on the vertices.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
          </md>
          To calculate <m>R_2 \circ F_3</m>, we can use these vertex
          changes. In composition, we do the right transformation
          first. Therefore, starting at vertex 1, <m>F_3</m> send it
          to vertex 5, and then <m>R_2</m> sends vertex 5 to vertex 2.
          Therefore, the whole composition sends vertex 1 to vertex 2.
          We calculate the movement of the other four vertices
          similarly. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then we have to identify this transformation, since is still
          should be something in the group. It cannot be a rotation,
          since vertex 4 is fixed. The only rotation that fixes vertex
          4 is <m>F_4</m>. Therefore, we have <m>R_2 \circ F_3 =
          F_4</m>. Note that the multiplication is not commutative. If
          we did <m>F_3 \circ R_2</m>, we would have these vertex
          transformations.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
          </md>
          This is the reflection <m>F_2</m>, so <m>F_3 \circ R_2</m>.
          Using similar vertex calcluation for all the entries, we
          produce the following multiplication table for <m>D_5</m>.
          <table>
            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor"
              right="minor">
              <row>
                <cell right="major" bottom="major"><m>\circ</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="major"><m>F_5</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="major"><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>F_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_4</m></cell>
                <cell><m>R_2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\Id</m></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular> 
          </table>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-week9-proofs">
    <title>Proof Questions</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the inverse of an orthogonal transformation is
          also orthogonal.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This is relatively easy to argue based on the concept and
          main definition.  Orthogonal matrices preserve lenghts. If
          lenghts do not change when we do a transformation forward,
          then also can't change when we unto the transformation and
          go backwards.  Undoing no change is still no change.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the composition of orthogonal transformations is
          still orthogonal. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Like the previous proof, I can argue this conceptually using
          the basic definition. If two transformations preserve
          lengths, then doing them one after another will also
          preserve lengths. Lenghts can't change in the first step and
          can't change in the second step, so they can't change at
          all. Therefore, the composition (doing one transformation
          after the other) must also be orthogonal. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that all orthogonal matrices have determinant <m>\pm
          1</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For this proof, I'm going to use one of the algebraic
          properties of orthogonal matrices.
          <me>
            A^TA = \Id
          </me>
          Then I'll take the determinant of both sides of this matrix
          equation.
          <me>
            \det(A^TA) = \det(\Id)
          </me>
          The determinant of the identity is 1. On the left side, the
          determinant is multiplicative. 
          <me>
            \det(A^T)\det(A) = 1
          </me>
          One of the properties of the determinant is that the
          determinant of a transpose is the same at the determinant of
          the original. 
          <me>
            \det(A)\det(A) = 1 \implies \det(A)^2 = 1
          </me>
          So the number <m>\det (A)</m> is a number which squares to
          <m>1</m>. The only numbers with this property are <m>1</m>
          and <m>-1</m>. That completes the proof.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the rotations and the reflections are the only
          orthogonal transformations in <m>\RR^2</m>. (This one is a
          lot trickiers than the previous proofs. Give is a shot, but
          don't distress too much if the approach is difficult to
          find.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This proof is substantially more difficult to approach that
          the three previous one. There are many transformation in
          <m>\RR^2</m>. We can't even just prove this for the five
          basic types, since there are complicated transformations
          that are combinations of the types and the combination might
          be orthogonal even when the pieces aren't. I need to find a
          trick or idea that let's me approach this.
        </p>
        <p>
          The idea I thought to use was acting on the standard basis:
          <m>\{e_1, e_2\}</m>. Since these two vectors span all of
          <m>\RR^2</m>, if we know what happens to these two vector,
          we know the entire transformation. First, the transformation does
          something to <m>e^1</m>, sending it to <m>Me_1</m>. Since
          length is preserved, this is some other unit vector. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Now where can <m>e_2</m> go? There are, in fact, only two
          choices. <m>Me_2</m> must also be a unit vector, since
          lengths are preserved. Also, angles are preserved, so the
          angle between the <m>Me_1</m> and <m>Me_2</m> must still be
          <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> (they are still perpendicular). That
          gives only two choices. If we face in the direction of
          <m>Me_2</m>, then we can have the unit vector pointing in
          the perpendicular direction to the right or two the left. 
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>Me_2</m> is the perpendicular direction to the left,
          then <m>M</m> is a rotation. The relative positions of the
          two vectors are preserved and they are still unit vectors,
          so the are moved around the circle by whatever the angle is
          between <m>e_1</m> and <m>Me_1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>ME_2</m> is the perpendicular direction to the right,
          then <m>M</m> is a reflection. This is a bit trickier to
          see, but the line of reflection will be the line halfway
          between <m>e_1</m> and <m>Me_1</m>. That line will flip
          <m>e_1</m> into <m>Me_1</m> by construction. But the flip
          will take anything perpendicular on the right and flip it so
          something perpendicular on the left. So <m>e_2</m>, which
          starts as the perpendicular vector on the right, ends up as
          the perpendicular direction on the left. 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M</m> must have one of these two behaviours, so <m>M</m>
          must be a rotation or a reflection.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
